Comment:

Patch Set 3:

The problem is that your patch only covers a case where WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS is received just before posting the event. If WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS is received after some event handler calls postEvent(), this patch doesn't help.

Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 3:
> 
> The problem is that your patch only covers a case where WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS is received just before posting the event. If WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS is received after some event handler calls postEvent(), this patch doesn't help.

The problem as I understand it requires two threads, so that the state of wakeUps, and the availability of a WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS in the message queue can go out of sync. If wakesUps is set but there's no more WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS, then we likely end up with processEvents blocking.

If an event is posted by a thread in a QObject::event handler (that's how I interpret your statement), then there's no multi-threadedness going on. wakeUps will always be reset by the sendPostedEvents that delivered the event that resulted in a postEvent; and so postEvent will always result in a new WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS being posted.

Can you elaborate or augment the test case?

Also, do you think this patch is wrong, or does it simply not fix all possible scenarios?

Patch Set 3:

> If an event is posted by a thread in a QObject::event handler (that's how I interpret your statement), then there's no multi-threadedness going on. wakeUps will always be reset by the sendPostedEvents that delivered the event that resulted in a postEvent; and so postEvent will always result in a new WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS being posted.

But, what happens if another thread posts an event while WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS hasn't been received yet?

Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 3:
> 
> > If an event is posted by a thread in a QObject::event handler (that's how I interpret your statement), then there's no multi-threadedness going on. wakeUps will always be reset by the sendPostedEvents that delivered the event that resulted in a postEvent; and so postEvent will always result in a new WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS being posted.
> 
> Yes, you are right.
> 
> > Also, do you think this patch is wrong, or does it simply not fix all possible scenarios?
> 
> The patch looks good for me now. But, I'm a little confused by the comment from QCoreApplicationPrivate::sendPostedEvents():
> 
> // by default, we assume that the event dispatcher can go to sleep after
> // processing all events. if any new events are posted while we send
> // events, canWait will be set to false.
> 
> Then it sets canWait to true which we check in the event dispatcher before blocking. So, is it okay not to block if pending posted events have been processed but new events have not been posted?

QCoreApplication::postEvent sets canWait (of the receiver's thread) to false; and if canWait is false, then QCoreApplicationPrivate::sendPostedEvents wakes up the event dispatcher.

So either we already have a QEvent posted by the time we are done with the while-loop flushing the windows message queue; in that case, canWait is false. Or we don't, in which case we can block, and another thread posting will wake us up.

If a receiver responds to an event delivered to it by sendPostedEvents while canWait is still true, then canWait will be false. The new event will not yet be sent (that's the offset logic in sendPostedEvents), and the WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS will no longer be in the message queue after the flushing while-loop completes, but since we don't wait anyway, it doesn't matter.

Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 3:
> 
> > If an event is posted by a thread in a QObject::event handler (that's how I interpret your statement), then there's no multi-threadedness going on. wakeUps will always be reset by the sendPostedEvents that delivered the event that resulted in a postEvent; and so postEvent will always result in a new WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS being posted.
> 
> But, what happens if another thread posts an event while WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS hasn't been received yet?

We PostMessage WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS to the receiver thread's message queue after the QEvent has been added to the receiver's event queue. wakeUps is then set.

If we are before sendPostedEvents, then no problem; the event is delivered, there's nothing more to do, we can wait (wakeUps not reset, nothing left in the QEvent-queue).

If we are after the flushing while loop, then no problem either; the WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS will stay in the queue and wake up MsgWaitForMultipleObjects, but doesn't get dispatched. wakeUps is reset by the next round when sendPostedEvents gets called.

If the receiver is in the message flushing while loop, then the newly posted WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS gets removed by the PeekMessage; but wakeUps is already set (by the sender's postEvent setting it after the receiver's sendPostedEvents resetting it). We need to now reset it - that's what the patch does. We won't wait anyway (canWait is false thanks to the posting).

Not sure if I understand your question correctly though.

Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 3:
> 
> > If an event is posted by a thread in a QObject::event handler (that's how I interpret your statement), then there's no multi-threadedness going on. wakeUps will always be reset by the sendPostedEvents that delivered the event that resulted in a postEvent; and so postEvent will always result in a new WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS being posted.
> 
> But, what happens if another thread posts an event while WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS hasn't been received yet?

PS: FWIW, the worst thing that I think can happen with this change is that wakeUp() posts a WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS message even though there already is one in the queue. And while this can in principle result in the message queue being flooded by such messages if (perhaps several) threads post events to the same receiver faster than the receiver can consume them - then this is a problem anyway even without the wakeUp-throttling (as the QEvents will pile up).

Patch Set 4:

> PS: FWIW, the worst thing that I think can happen with this change is that wakeUp() posts a WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS message even though there already is one in the queue. And while this can in principle result in the message queue being flooded by such messages if (perhaps several) threads post events to the same receiver faster than the receiver can consume them - then this is a problem anyway even without the wakeUp-throttling (as the QEvents will pile up).

This is another problem. Posted events have the highest priority in the Windows queue. So, most likely the next message GetMessage() gets after calling postEvent() will be WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS. That's why I didn't put 'wakeUps.storeRelaxed(0)' here.

Patch Set 4:

> Patch Set 4:
> 
> > PS: FWIW, the worst thing that I think can happen with this change is that wakeUp() posts a WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS message even though there already is one in the queue. And while this can in principle result in the message queue being flooded by such messages if (perhaps several) threads post events to the same receiver faster than the receiver can consume them - then this is a problem anyway even without the wakeUp-throttling (as the QEvents will pile up).
> 
> This is another problem. Posted events have the highest priority in the Windows queue. So, most likely the next message GetMessage() gets after calling postEvent() will be WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS. That's why I didn't put 'wakeUps.storeRelaxed(0)' here.

retVal is set to true in the loop when the first WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS is seen by the inner loop; and the inner loop never calls sendPostedEvents, so no new WM_QT_SENDPOSTEDEVENTS will be posted (at least not by that thread; again, if another thread bombards the event processing thread with stuff DoS style, then all bets are off anyway). Then canWait becomes false, and the outer do/while loop exits.

So that shouldn't be a problem as such, posted events are still send by the next call to processEvents.

Would be good to add more test cases for this, perhaps - reasoning about this by looking at the code is only gets us so far :)

Patch Set 4:

> But is that a bug? You post two events, you get two events, and then the event loop blocks because you ask it to wait for more events, which never come from anywhere.

Yes. On Unix, running this example gives me
 
1 Ping
1 Pong
2 Ping
2 Pong

and I expect the same result on macOS. Comment from qeventdispatcher_cf.mm:

"If the WaitForMoreEvents is set, the function should wait only if there were no events ready"

So, we must avoid blocking when sendPostedEvents() delivers the second event. The same problem occurs in the multi-threaded example.

Patch Set 4:

> Patch Set 4:
> 
> > But is that a bug? You post two events, you get two events, and then the event loop blocks because you ask it to wait for more events, which never come from anywhere.
> 
> Yes. On Unix, running this example gives me
>  
> 1 Ping
> 1 Pong
> 2 Ping
> 2 Pong
> 
> and I expect the same result on macOS. Comment from qeventdispatcher_cf.mm:
> 
> "If the WaitForMoreEvents is set, the function should wait only if there were no events ready"
> 
> So, we must avoid blocking when sendPostedEvents() delivers the second event. The same problem occurs in the multi-threaded example.

Ok, then Linux and macOS dispatchers work differently. But looking at the code, how can we implement this on Windows? With sendPostedEvents not returning any information about whether events were send by the call, how can processEvents decide that it must not wait? sendPostedEvents sets canWait to false if it didn’t deliver all events (data->postEventListSize() == 0 and a few lines later always to true in QCoreApplicationPrivate::sendPostedEvents, before the sending of the event); in your example that sets canWait to true, then the event delivery sets canWait to false when the event handler posts; the first processEvents call doesn’t block.

Then we go into the second loop, the posted event is sent, canWait is set to true (all events were sent), nothing sets ot to dalse, the processEvent blocks.

This is using the unix event dispatcher btw, if I instantiate QCoreApplication. If I instantiate QApplication, then it uses the QCocoaEventDispatcher, which behaves like you describe.

This is all a bloody mess it seems :( But I think the fix is still the right fix; that the unix and win32 event dispatcher block even though sendPostedEvents delivered events is a different bug.

Debugging a bit more with Cooca (ie QApplication instantiated rather than QCoreApplication) QThreadData::canWait is during the second processEvents call; but retVal is also true, because there're several NSEvents in the native queue; some of them kit-defined, some of them app defined. I have no idea right now where they come from.

Why does the event dispatcher (perhaps the glib event dispatcher) not block in your case? Surely QThreadData::canWait is true on Linux as well after the sendPostedEvents?

Patch Set 4:

I haven't had a chance to look into the details of this issue, but a small clarification/data point:

 - QEventDispatcherCoreFoundation was written for iOS. It's used in these cases:
   - As a base class for QIOSEventDispatcher which is the GUI-event dispatcher on iOS
   - For secondary threads on iOS/macOS if and only if QT_EVENT_DISPATCHER_CORE_FOUNDATION is set (experimental functionality). Otherwise QEventDispatcherUNIX is used.

 - QCocoaEventDispatcher was written for macOS, and is used as the GUI dispatcher there
   - Secondary threads use QEventDispatcherUNIX (unless the CF dispatcher is explicitly requested)

That is, for a normal GUI app you'll primarily be interacting with QEventDispatcherCoreFoundation on iOS, and QCocoaEventDispatcher on macOS. For non-GUI apps and secondary threads it will be QEventDispatcherUNIX on both.

Patch Set 4:

In my local testing:

 - QEventDispatcherUNIX: blocks after second ping
 - QEventDispatcherCoreFoundation: ping/pong x 2
 - QCocoaEventDispatcher: ping/pong x 2

I believe the correct behavior is to see two ping/pongs, without blocking. This is based on the understanding that WaitForMoreEvents should only block if there are no events to process (docs say "Wait for events if no pending events are available"). If we do process an event (any event, system or Qt) then the processEvents() call should return (unless exec or other flags say so). 

In the test-case by Alex this is true for both passes. The first pass has an event queued up by main(). The second pass has an event queued up by EventReceiver::event, which doesn't get processed by the current call to processEvent since that should already process already queued events.

But, as Volker says, the blocking behavior might be a different bug than what this patch tries to solve. I haven't looked into the code of this patch yet.

PS: Worth noting is that even without manually posting any Qt events, WaitForMoreEvents might still not block, since the processEvents call might process non-Qt (system) events, so we cannot test for the opposite.

messages.message:
Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2 Sanity-Review+1

Apparently pushing a Work In Progress
Uploaded patch set 2: Commit message was updated.
Uploaded patch set 4: Commit message was updated.

Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

I think the intention behind the current design is that the compositor is optional. For example we don't need it if the screen has one fullscreen window. Also, it currently supports raster windows only (so no OpenGL support).

This design works as well, and does move all of the logic nicely into one location. If there is a single fullscreen window only then the compositor would then be disabled, or would just pass through the events.

Apparently pushing a Work In Progress

[*] Please note, Qt prefers American English.

See http://wiki.qt.io/Early_Warning_System for explanations.
Uploaded patch set 4: Commit message was updated.

Patch Set 4:

That's another attempt, more involving than a previous one (the one I'd still prefer, even if it somewhat not looking native), with some consequences (how about not having blue buttons anymore!)

Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

Looking at the Apple documentation for NSButtonType it seems we should be always using NSButtonTypeMomentaryPushIn for our normal buttons. 

https://developer.apple.com/documentation/appkit/nsbuttontype?language=objc

I suspect we've been using NSButtonTypePushOnPushOff so that we could use the "on" state to deal with both pressed and default button style, but that seems fragile (as we've seen with macOS 12).

Would it be possible to use NSButtonTypeMomentaryPushIn for our normal buttons, and then deal with default button styling by setting a key equivalent of \r, as is the documentation way of making a button the default button? That would decouple the button type from whether it's a default button or not.

Patch Set 4:

good hint about key equivalent - in my test it makes all buttons behave differently (meaning if needed they have the blue color even if it's not push-on/push-off). working on updated patch.

Abandoned

too contrived to be reliable, we have a simpler solution, using one button type.

Packaging feature tells export tool what build targets to export, packaging then includes these exported targets in releases.

From the wiki: The -developer-build option is not meant for shipping applications, but can be used for developing Qt.
